targeting the security and reliability of cross-chain communication
protocols" through formal mathematical grounding. Surveys classify what
protocols do (e.g., "lock-and-mint"), but they do not analyze the formal
invariants or properties (like conservation or causality) that must be
preserved at a semantic level across these transitions.

While these surveys establish that interoperability protocols are
functionally categorized, they do not analyze whether asset and data
interoperability impose fundamentally different semantic requirements.
This distinction is explored in the following sections by examining
asset-specific mechanisms first, followed by data-specific mechanisms.

** Asset Interoperability Mechanisms
:PROPERTIES:
:CUSTOM_ID: asset-interoperability-mechanisms
:END:
Asset interoperability refers to the capacity for autonomous and diverse
blockchain networks to interact, exchange, and transfer digital assets,
including fungible tokens, cryptocurrencies, and non-fungible tokens
(NFTs). As the blockchain ecosystem has grown increasingly heterogeneous
and fragmented into "digital islands," asset interoperability has
emerged as a critical requirement for market penetration and user
flexibility. By enabling the movement of value across disparate ledgers,
interoperability protocols reduce liquidity fragmentation and mitigate
the risk of vendor lock-in for investors.

The most prevalent communication model for cross-chain asset transfer is
the lock-and-mint mechanism [cite:@belenkov2025review]. This is often
used to create wrapped representations of native assets on secondary
chains. In this model, the process begins when a user initiates a
transaction to deposit and lock a specific amount of native assets. This
is done into a custodian contract on the source chain. Then, the source
contract places the assets in an unusable state and emits a Deposit
event. This event contains the transaction details. An off-chain relayer
or communicator network observes this event, verifies its authenticity,
and submits a signed proof to a debt issuer contract on the destination
chain. Once the verification of the proof is successful, the destination
contract now mints a corresponding amount of wrapped tokens to the
recipient's address [cite:@eurocom].

The system utilises a burn and release or burn and mint mechanism to
return the assets to their original native chain. The user now initiates
this process by calling a "burn" function on the destination chain. This
will permanently destroy the wrapped tokens to remove them from the
circulating supply. This action then triggers a "Burn" event. This event
is fetched and verified by the off-chain communicator. Once the burn is
confirmed, the communicator submits a release transaction to the source
chain's custodian contract. The custodian will unlock and release the
original native assets back to the user's account once the verifying of
the burn proof is complete.

Atomic swaps are unlike the bridge-based models. The do not rely on
intermediaries. Instead, they faciliate the simultaneous exchange of
assets between two parties on different blockchains. That is also
without requiring a trusted thid party. This mechanism ensures
"all-or-nothing" execution through the use of Hashed Time-Locked
Contracts (HTLC). HTLCs utilize cryptographic hashlocks and timelocks to
conditionally lock assets. Here, the transaction only completes if a
secret preimage is revealed within a specific timeframe. If the
initiator reveals the secret to claim their new asset, the counterparty
automatically gains the secret to claim the reciprocal asset. This
ensures mathematical atomicity across the two ledgers.

However, recurring bridge exploits still have resulted in losses
exceeding $2.8 billion due to improper implementation of value
accounting. Eventhought it has sophisticated design. The security
analyses of major hacks, such as those targeting Ronin, Wormhole, and
Nomad, identify the shared root cause as a violation of end-to-end
financial logic. The outflow here was allowed to exceed inflow.
Specifically, attackers have exploited vulnerabilities to mint assets
out of thin air without corresponding deposits. For example, the Qubit
exploit involved a logical error that allowed an attacker to trigger a
"Deposit" event without transferring any real assets. This leads to the
unauthorized withdrawal of millions on the destination chain. Other
failures, such as the Ronin and Harmony hacks, also occurred when
attackers compromised validator keys to forge signatures that satisfied
access control invariants.

The literature emphasizes that several fundamental properties must hold
in order to ensure the safety of cross-chain asset transfers. The core
requirement is value conservation. This states that the total supply of
an asset must remain constant across the combined state of both
participating ledgers. This is often formalized as a balance invariant.
In this case, the value of minted or released tokens must equal the
value of deposited tokens minus costs. Furthermore, bridges must
maintain a strict 1-to-1 relationship between locked assets and their
wrapped counterparts to prevent double-spending and unauthorized
inflation. These properties ensure that even if a bridge "dies" or
becomes unresponsive, the underlying financial state remains reachable
and verifiable for recovery.

While these mechanisms are well-studied, their semantic invariants are
rarely formalized separately from general message passing, often
obscuring the distinct economic risks inherent in asset-driven state
transitions.

** Data Interoperability Mechanisms
:PROPERTIES:
:CUSTOM_ID: data-interoperability-mechanisms
:END:
Data interoperability is often characterized as cross-chain messaging or
state communication. It refers to the "creation of protocols, data
models, and data mapping mechanisms that facilitate the seamless
exchange of data across disparate blockchain networks" [cite:@eurocom].
Unlike asset interoperability data interoperability enables one ledger
"to trigger actions or respond to events occurring on another ledger".
What this mean is that it treats the target chain as a remote
computational environment. This is fundamentally different from the
asset transfer because this involves the copying of information from one
DLT to another. That so rather than ensuring the exclusive movement of a
finite resource. Consequently, this supports more different use cases
such as the cross-ledger governance or voting, the account delegation,
and the arbitrary contract calls.

A common example of data interoperability is the Inter-Blockchain
Communication (IBC) protocol [cite:@goes2020interblockchain]. It has a
stateful and authenticated data passing in the literature. IBC is
modeled after the TCP/IP stack. It utilizes the bottom-up approach that
separates the core transport, authentication, and ordering (TAO) layer
from the application (APP) layer [cite:@wei2023formal]. This protocol
operates through a series of structured handshakes to establish
connections and channels. The connection handshakes involves four
distinct steps which are: OpenInit, OpenTry, OpenAck, and OpenConfirm.
That is to ensure that both ledgers have reached agreement on each
other's identifiers and consensus states [cite:@wei2023formal]. IBC
packets are formally "opaque" to the transport layer. This allows its
modules on each ledger to determine their own semantics while the
protocol guarantees reliable, ordered, and authenticated communication
[cite:@goes2020interblockchain].

Data transport in decentralized systems relies on "relayer processes".
They are untrusted and off-chain agents responsible for scanning each
chain, constructing appropriate datagrams, and submitting transactions
to the destination [cite:@wei2023formal]. The security of these systems
is rooted in light-client verification. In light-client verification,
the destination chain maintains a "lightweight representation" or block
headers of the source chain. Its purpose is to verify cryptographic
proofs such as Merkle proofs for specific messages without storing the
entire ledger history [cite:@wei2023formal]. What changes here is in the
trust assumption. It is now shifted from the relayer to the validator
set of the connected blockchain itself. This is because the
light-clients are the one that verify the source chain's consensus or
finality rules. This model can be efficient for resource-constrained
environments like mobile devices since the gas limits prohibits the full
node verification.

Trusted interoperability operates in contrast to the trustless nature of
light clients. In trusted interoperability, we utilise the notary
schemes or oracle-based messaging [cite:@lu2024atomicity]. This rely on
a threshold of signers or committees or multisignature sets. They attest
that an event occurred on a source chain [cite:@sherlock2026cross].
Similarly, oracle networks like Chainlink's "Cross-Chain
Interoperability Protocol (CCIP)" also uses Decentralized Oracle
Networks (DONs). DONs verifies and routes messages off-chain. Then it
reaches an off-chain consensus before delivering data to the destination
router [cite:@yellow.com]. These protocols avoid heavy on-chain header
verification. This makes them simpler to implement and faster to
execute. However, this introduces a centralisation of trust because the
security now depends entirely on the honesty of the majority of notaries
rather than on the honestly of the native chain consensus
[cite:@bondarchuk2025security].

For data interoperability to be correct, there are several properties
that must hold: the safety the ordering and causality, and the secure
transfer property. The safety property requires that messages cannot be
forged; and its destination must treat a claim as authorized. That is
only if it originates from a verified source domain
[cite:@lu2024atomicity]. The ordering and causality dictates that
protocols must provide ordering guarantees, that is ordered or unordered
channels, in order to allow applications to reason about the combined
state of connected modules. Also, it ensure that state changes are
correctly bound to the events that caused them
[cite:@goes2020interblockchain]. The secure transfer property mandates
that a receiver should only process a message once the source-chain
event has been committed and cannot be rolled back
[cite:@lu2024atomicity]. Critically, for data interoperability,
conservation is NOT a requirement. That is because in data transfer, the
transfer is defined as a process of copying information. Duplication is
also often allowed at the transport level [cite:@eurocom]. Formal
analyses of the IBC TAO layer explicitly note that while assets require
conservation of supply, pure data transport on the other hand is
payload-agnostic and does not inherently enforce a supply invariant.
That is unless implemented by the application logic
[cite:@goes2020interblockchain].

Security research in cross-chain messaging highlights vulnerabilities
that target data integrity and verification logic. A prominent failure
class is the verification bypass. It was seen in the Nomad hack. That
time, there was an initialization error caused the system to treat
"untrusted roots" (0x00) as proven. This allowed the attackers to forge
arbitrary messages [cite:@Google]. Other risks include replay attacks.
In that case, a lack of domain separation allows a valid message to be
reused across different pathways [cite:@sherlock2026cross]. Formal
modeling using TLA+ has further identified "incomplete handshakes" and
"trapped packets" as protocol-level liveness risks. These can lead to
permanent state inconsistencies between connected chains
[cite:@wei2023formal].

** Semantic Compatibility Issues
:PROPERTIES:
:CUSTOM_ID: semantic-compatibility-issues
:END:
Blockchain semantic compatibility refers to the shared and accurate
meaning of exchanged information. It also refers to the consistent
interpretation across heterogeneous distributed systems. It involves
understanding the meaning embedded in the information. This is done by
interpreting the data context, relationships, and semantics. So to
ensure that the consuming system correctly understands the intent of the
source ledger. Semantic compatibility is an ongoing challenge
[cite:@belchior2021survey]. While technical and functional layers of
interoperability have been extensively explored, few solutions focus on
the semantic layer. The importance of semantics is paramount. Without
it, there would be no shared meanings. Systems may interpret the same
message or state transition differently. This can lead to friction to
translate concepts, inaccurate mapping, and catastrophic logical errors
in gestalt multi-ledger applications [cite:@sottomayor2024enterprise].

The existing literature contains multiple explicit statements regarding
the unresolved nature of semantic formalization. Authors consistently
characterize these gaps as "open problems" or "limitations" of current
research:

Researchers note that the field "lacks a unified definition of what
blockchain is" and that "no such widely accepted reference architecture
exists" for DLT interoperability. Neglected Semantic Exploration: There
is a significant gap in "capturing semantic information" from code;
research in this specific area has received "less to no emphasis". A
noted limitation is the "lack of unified frameworks that integrate
multiple reasoning strategies" to verify complex inter-dependent
requirements across chains. To date, there is a noted "lack of research
explicitly targeting the security and reliability of cross-chain
communication protocols" through rigorous formal mathematical grounding.

Beyond these explicit statements, there is a core implicit gap regarding
the formal distinction between asset and data interoperability. An
analysis of current formal models reveals that papers typically either
generalize both categories into a single abstraction or focus on one in
isolation. For instance, an abstract state machine model
\((V, \Sigma,T)\) is modelled for multi-chain atomicity but this treat
asset exchange merely as a specific instance of an arbitrary smart
contract action [cite:@lu2024atomicity]. This fails to mathematically
distinguish the unique economic logic of value from the integrity logic
of data. A formalization of the IBC TAO layer also exists
[cite:@wei2023formal]. However, they explicitly state the protocol is
payload-agnostic. This means that the state machine itself does not
reason about the difference between a token transfer and a governance
vote [cite:@goes2020interblockchain]. Furthermore, no paper provides a
unified semantic framework capable of simultaneously classifying and
verifying both types. This research gap is highly problematic for the
security of cross-chain systems. Lee et al. (2022) and Liu et al. (2024)
demonstrate that massive bridge exploits frequently stem from invariant
violations. What happens is assets were minted out of thin air because
the system allowed unbalanced transitions. Mixing asset and data
semantics leads to under-specified guarantees. This may cause designers
to inadvertently apply copy-based data rules, for example, to assets
(leading to unauthorized inflation) or "conservation-based" rules to
pure data. The former will lead to unathorised inflation meanwhile the
latter will lead to over-constrained, inefficient systems. Verification
becomes ambiguous because it is unclear whether a safety property like
finality refers to the economic finality of a token or to the delivery
finality of a message.

