While the literature successfully provides descriptive taxonomies and
individual protocol audits, it lacks a unified formal state machine
model that mathematically distinguishes the semantic properties of asset
interoperability (governed by value conservation) from those of data
interoperability (governed by message integrity). This fragmentation
leaves cross-chain developers without a rigorous framework to verify
"gestalt" applications that simultaneously manage financial value and
informational state.

This research addresses the aforementioned gap by moving beyond
feature-based classification toward a mathematically verifiable
architecture. The following chapter presents a theoretical framework
that formalizes this semantic distinction using abstract
state-transition models and invariant analysis to ensure that both
economic and computational safety can be proven across heterogeneous
domains.

